<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18600507-493">
               <interp inst="t18600507-493" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18600507"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18600507-493" type="date" value="18600507"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18600507-493-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-493-18600507 t18600507-493-offence-1 t18600507-493-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>493. <persName id="def1-493-18600507" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-493-18600507" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-493-18600507" type="age" value="34"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-493-18600507" type="surname" value="GAY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-493-18600507" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN GAY</hi> (34)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18600507-493-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18600507-493-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18600507-493-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp>, Feloniously cutting and wounding <persName id="t18600507-name-690" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-690" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-690" type="surname" value="GAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-690" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18600507-493-offence-1 t18600507-name-690"></join>Mary Ann Gay</persName> upon her neck and throat, with intent to murder her. <hi rend="italic">Second Count.</hi> To do her some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-691" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-691" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-691" type="surname" value="GAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-691" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN GAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prisoner's wife—on 5th April, I was living apart from him at Mrs. Clement's, 5, Park-lane, Clapham—I did live at 4, Mill-row, Clapham, and I went from there to Mrs. Clements—I went to try to get a lodging—no one would take me in on account of my husband—on 5th April, I saw my husband—I had been washing and I saw him against the door of the lodging—he asked me to give him a little hat brush, and I said yes, and he followed me into the passage and asked if I would have a little beer—I said, "No"—I went up stairs and got the hat brush and gave it him—I went out and left him there—I met Mrs. Clements, and I told her he was in the house—I returned with Mrs. Clements—I went in doors and sat down, and he sat down by the side of me—he went and got some beer and asked me to drink with him, and I did so—Mrs. Clements asked him to go, and I asked him myself to go—he said he had very comfortable lodgings—I said I was very glad of it, and I told him not to trouble me and I would not trouble him—he was going, and he came to the foot of the stairs and asked me to shake hands with him, and I did so—he then asked me to stop the night with him—I said,"No, you said you had a comfortable lodging, go to your lodging"—he then said he would stop—Mrs. Clements</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070200"></xptr>
               <p>said she hoped he would not come there, it was a quiet place and we did not want to have a noise—he again asked me to stop—I said, "No," and he left—on the following morning about 6 o'clock, I was getting my break<lb></lb>fast, Mrs. Clements was gone to work, and Mr. Clements was out; there were two children in the house—while getting my breakfast a knock came at the door; I went to the door and it was my husband—he asked me for a bag which he had left the night before—I said he had not left a bag there, I supposed he had left it in his room at night and had forgotten it—I looked round for the bag and I said there was no one there—he then asked me for some water—I said, "Why do you not go to your lodging"—he then said with an oath that he would cut my throat, and before the words were out of his mouth I felt the cut at my throat—I struggled with him very much and defended the cut off with my hand, and he cut the leaders of my left hand—I fell and he fell on me—he rose, and he was endeavouring to cut my throat—I fell down and was on my knees—I struggled and got the razor from him, and he put his fingers in my throat to tear the wound open—the wound bled very much indeed; it bled much more after that—my husband got up and ran away—I was very much exhausted—I hallooed murder as long as I could, and some gentleman came and said I had cut my throat as I had the razor in my hand—I said no, my husband had done it—I saw Mrs. Clements and asked her to run for a doctor, and I was taken to the hospital—I don't know of any cause for this—my husband has not been happy with me for the last three years—I believe it was jealousy, but I believe the jealousy has been on the wrong side—I have had two warrants and a summons for him for his ill usage, and the last time he said if I had him brought up again, he would give me something for it—that is about a month ago.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. TINDAL ATKINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you been married to him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Eleven years on the 27th of last December—I did not leave him by agreement; he left me—he left me with the furniture in the house—he left me in debt—he went to lodgings—I removed the articles away from my own house—he asked me whether I had sold the things, and I did not tell him—I said, I had the things there, but I had to pay for them—we have not been happy together for the last three years—it was at my suggestion that he left me—when he came to me this time he did not appear to be in liquor—I observed something about him that I did not like—there was a wildness about him—it was quite unusual for me to see him look so—I did not go and leave him three years ago; he left me—there was a lodger staying with me when my husband was with me; that was Mary Ann Donald—I never had any male person lodge there—I never left the prisoner with any male person; I don't recollect that I did—I did not leave him three years ago for a little while; he left me—I did not live with any man that time—I never lived with a man since I have known my husband—I know a man of the name of Metcalfe, he never stayed with me any time—I never had any improper connexion with any man since I was married.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-692" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-692" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-692" type="surname" value="CLEMENTS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-692" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH CLEMENTS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Park-lane, Clapham—my husband is a carrier, and I go out to work as a laundress—Mrs. Gay was living with me—on 5th April I saw the prisoner in the street, he Baid, "Is that Mrs. Clements?"—I said, "Yes"—he said he wanted to see Polly, meaning his wife—I went back and there was the prisoner; he sat down by the side of his wife and pressed her very much to have some beer, and I wished her to take some because I was afraid he would make a noise—he fetched a pot of porter himself and she and I partook of it—my husband did not drink any—the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070201"></xptr>
               <p>I prisoner then wanted to fetch more beer, but I wished him to go—I said to I him, "Go"—he rose up to go, and then he asked his wife if she would let I him stop there that night—she said, "No" and I said, "No"—he went up the stairs and said he would stop with her—I told him she was only a I lodger and he could not—he came down again and went out at the door—I the next morning I saw Mrs. Gay bleeding from a wound in her throat—there was a great quantity of blood came from her, not so much in the kitchen, but in the passage there was a quantity of blood—I ran to the I doctor—the doctor came and dressed her throat, and she was taken to the I hospital—when I came back from the doctor the prisoner saw me in Acre-lane, and said I kept a regular b—y house and encouraged his w—e to I come there; there is not the least ground for saying I keep a house of that description—I never knew of any man living with the prisoner's wife; she I is a hard-working woman—I had seen the prisoner before—I have not heard him before make complaints of his wife.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is it a delusion to say that you keep an improper house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, it is—I don't know whether the prisoner was very wild when he was talking in that way, I did not look at him much.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-693" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-693" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-693" type="surname" value="YOUNG"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-693" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM YOUNG</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Park-place, No. 5 is at the back of me—about three minutes before 6 o'clock that morning, I was in my garden and heard screams—I went to No. 5 and saw Mrs. Gay, she was at the end of the passage on the edge of the kerb throwing her hands about and seemingly in great pain—she had at that time a razor in her hand—I took the razor from her and gave it to the policeman—the razor was bloody—I saw the prisoner about five minutes afterwards, I saw him wash his hands in a pond—I walked by his side till I met a policeman, and he gave himself up—after I gave up the razor at the station he gave up the sheath and said it belonged to it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-694" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-694" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-694" type="surname" value="NEWMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-694" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS NEWMAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Police-sergeant, V</hi> 25). About ten minutes after 6 o'clock that morning, I was on duty at Clapham—I saw the prisoner followed by the last witness and several others; they said, "Stop that man, he has cut his wife's throat"—the prisoner said, "I don't want to be stopped, I have done it, I was coming to the station to give myself up"—after I took him to the station, I went to the house and saw Mrs. Gay on the floor, the doctor was attending her—the place was bloody all over; the passage, the floor, and the walls—this is the razor I received from the last witness—the prisoner took this sheath of it out of his own pocket at the station—I think he said, "This is the sheath."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-695" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-695" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-695" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-695" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH WILLIAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am bar-maid at the Oxford-arms, Clapham—about 5 o'clock on the morning of the 6th April the prisoner came there—he had some brandy and ale—he remained till about a quarter before 6 o'clock; he then left and was away about ten minutes, he came back and asked for more brandy—he said, "I am going to pay you for it, this is the last I shall ever drink; I have out my wife's throat, I have come here to wait for the policeman to take me"—I begged him not to stop—his hands were covered with blood—he said, "Look here"—he just went in the parlour and then went away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-696" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-696" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-696" type="surname" value="DRUMMOND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-696" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA DRUMMOND</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 39, Park-place, opposite to where Mrs. Gay lived—on 6th April, about 6 o'clock, I heard several screams—I looked out of window and saw the prisoner and his wife struggling in the passage—his wife was upon her knees, and the prisoner seemed as if he was getting up from his wife—he was at her back—he rushed into the road and then ran up the street.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-697" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-697" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-697" type="surname" value="BUNKART"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-697" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES BUNKART</persName>
                  </hi>. I am house surgeon at Guy's Hospital—on the morn<lb></lb>ing</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070202"></xptr>
               <p>of 6th April, Mary Ann Gay was brought in—I did not see her till about 11 o'clock—she had two incised wounds on her throat, one about four inches long, extending from the left ear to the middle of the throat—the other was about two inches long, about an inch and a half below it, towards the centre of the throat; I should think about half an inch deep—they were cut from left to right—the principal depth was on the left side of the throat—she was not in danger—I found some small wounds on her hands.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Crost-examined. Q.</hi> They were not of depth enough to injure life? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, they were not—the principal wound was on the side of the neck—the cuts on the hands were such as would be made by attempting to defend the throat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did either of the wounds present the appearance of having been torn? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I could not judge that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were the ends of the wounds torn? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
